<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/19073906-keith"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1525256409i/19073906._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/19073906-keith">Keith</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    I think he made the decision because he was starting to realize that his quest was a wild goose chase (i.e. his parents were dead or irrevocably vanis<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    I think he made the decision because he was starting to realize that his quest was a wild goose chase (i.e. his parents were dead or irrevocably vanished, not absurdly imprisoned in the same house for decades) and people in the know were laughing at him behind his back. Sarah's invitation gave him an "out" where the decision was partly taken out of his hands.<br /><br />This was a classic "hero has the opportunity to turn aside from their path but doesn't" moment. Usually this is a positive moment for the hero and the story as a whole (they choose the right path rather than the easy and/or less moral one, or choose to do something good rather than doing nothing), but in this case (in keeping with the book's overall tone) it was a deflating moment, where Christopher seemed on the point of realizing the futility and delusion of his quest and seeking a normal life instead, but turned away at the last moment to "tilt at the windmill".<br /><br />(That said, Sarah said herself in her letter that it was perhaps better for Christopher to find closure.)<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
