    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1460571927" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1460571927" />
    <a title="Hugh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32318315-hugh"><img alt="Hugh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1466451007p2/32318315.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1460571927?book_show_action=true">Dec 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hugh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hugh" href="/user/show/32318315-hugh">Hugh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780571283880" href="/book/show/15929365-when-we-were-orphans">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=modern-lit">modern-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=read-2016">read-2016</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32318315-hugh?shelf=booker-shortlist">booker-shortlist</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1460571927" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17221752517274283701">This book is something of a weird trip. At first we are in similar territory to <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28921.The_Remains_of_the_Day' title='The Remains of the Day by Kazuo Ishiguro' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Remains of the Day</a>, in 1920s London, where we find the narrator as a young man making a name for himself as a detective, who has come to England from Shanghai after his parents disappeared. Then we move to Shanghai in 1937, where things gradually get messier and more surreal and develop into a Kafkaesque thrillerish nightmare set in a war zone as the narrator tries to resolve the story of his parents. This sectio</span>
  <span id="freeText17221752517274283701" style="display:none">This book is something of a weird trip. At first we are in similar territory to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28921.The_Remains_of_the_Day" title="The Remains of the Day by Kazuo Ishiguro" rel="nofollow noopener">The Remains of the Day</a>, in 1920s London, where we find the narrator as a young man making a name for himself as a detective, who has come to England from Shanghai after his parents disappeared. Then we move to Shanghai in 1937, where things gradually get messier and more surreal and develop into a Kafkaesque thrillerish nightmare set in a war zone as the narrator tries to resolve the story of his parents. This section was reminiscent of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40117.The_Unconsoled" title="The Unconsoled by Kazuo Ishiguro" rel="nofollow noopener">The Unconsoled</a>, but without the repetition and the longueurs that made that book a difficult read. Finally there is a short but moving resolution. <br /><br />The disjointed nature of the plot makes this a tricky one to assess, but it contains some fine writing and some interesting ideas about the nature of loss and the way lives are shaped by larger historical events, and the contrasts between European and Asian perspectives. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17221752517274283701" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


