    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2187808891" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2187808891" />
    <a title="Issicratea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23268828-issicratea"><img alt="Issicratea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1378040602p2/23268828.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2187808891?book_show_action=true">Nov 18, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Issicratea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Issicratea" href="/user/show/23268828-issicratea">Issicratea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780375724404" href="/book/show/136763.When_We_Were_Orphans">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23268828-issicratea?shelf=1990-2010">1990-2010</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23268828-issicratea?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2187808891" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6823449845845663963">I read two very interesting press reviews of <i>When We Were Orphans</i> just after finishing it, by Philip Hensher in The Guardian and Michael Gorra in The New York Times. Hensher’s is critical, judging <i>Orphans</i> to be a relative failure by comparison with <i>The Remains of the Day</i> and <i>The Unconsoled,</i> while Gorra sees it as Ishiguro’s finest achievement up to that point (in 2000.) I think I’m with Hensher in terms of evaluation, but my jury is still slightly out.<br/><br/>Certainly, these three novels are close enou</span>
  <span id="freeText6823449845845663963" style="display:none">I read two very interesting press reviews of <i>When We Were Orphans</i> just after finishing it, by Philip Hensher in The Guardian and Michael Gorra in The New York Times. Hensher’s is critical, judging <i>Orphans</i> to be a relative failure by comparison with <i>The Remains of the Day</i> and <i>The Unconsoled,</i> while Gorra sees it as Ishiguro’s finest achievement up to that point (in 2000.) I think I’m with Hensher in terms of evaluation, but my jury is still slightly out.<br /><br />Certainly, these three novels are close enough thematically to almost constitute a triptych—or polyptych, I guess, now, with <i>The Buried Giant</i>—and it’s a fascinating exercise to read them together (I have already decided I need to revisit <i>The Remains of the Day.</i>) The workings of memory; the relationships between memory and cognition, between memory and identity, between individual and collective memory—here are the threads that bind these very different novels together. They are rich enough themes, especially explored in Ishiguro’s oblique, allusive manner, to sustain a series without repetition of the inert kind. Instead we have repetition of the aesthetically sustaining kind: half-buried consonances and echoes, recurrent motifs.<br /><br />Unlike <i>The Unconsoled</i> and <i>The Buried Giant, When We Were Orphans</i> has a precise, historical setting; indeed, the chapter headings locate successive episodes very exactly in time. The protagonist, Christopher Banks, spent his childhood in Shanghai, in the International Settlement, before being shipped back to England as a young boy after the loss of his parents in mysterious circumstances. The novel opens with him as a young man in 1920s London, establishing himself as a society detective (a detail handled in a charmingly semi-parodic manner.) Later, he returns to Shanghai, nominally to find his parents, and he is plunged into the horrors of the 1937 Sino-Japanese battle through that city. One extraordinary, oneiric scene sees him wandering by night through the devastated slumland war zone.<br /><br />Something I like about the reviews by Hensher and Gorra (links to which I’ll copy at the end of this) is that they focus on Ishiguro’s style and technique, which are undoubtedly pivotal to the distinctiveness and power of his novels, far more than elements such as character, plot, or setting. In a very acute self-analysis cited by Gorra, Ishiguro defines his style as one that “suppresses meaning” and he speaks then of “tackling on a thematic level the implications” of that style. I like that suggestion that the whole architecture of Ishiguro’s novels, with their curiously bleached-out, dissonant settings, and their self-deceiving and unreliable narrators—step forward, Mr Banks—derive at some fundamental level from a linguistic and stylistic choice. We all know that the novelist’s instrument, language, is something as apt to disguise or traduce meaning as it is to convey it; yet few novelists explore the implications of that insight with Ishiguro’s inventiveness and rigor.<br /><br />Hensher sees <i>When We Were Orphans</i> as a qualified failure because it eschews the carefully rarified, dream-like world of <i>The Unconsoled</i> and ventures into territory we would expect to be tackled by a writer with a more full-bloodied, descriptive prose style. I had a little of the same reaction myself when I was reading the long episode set in the nightmarish war zones of Shanghai. We are used to seeing this kind of visceral material clothed in a far more visceral style (I am thinking of something like Andrey McGee’s remarkable description of the siege of Stalingrad in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18807408.The_Undertaking" title="The Undertaking by Audrey Magee" rel="nofollow noopener">The Undertaking</a>.) Ishiguro, instead, describes the horrors Christopher Banks stumbles through in Banks’ own prim, fussy, flat “meaning-suppressing” voice. <br /><br />As I say, at the time I was reading it, I found this dissonance of style and subject matter disconcerting, but, at a little distance, I wonder whether this was just a problem of expectations. The episode remains in my mind as very powerful, perhaps all the more so because it disrupted my expectations. It is an experience of war-time horror filtered through the mechanisms of a peculiar, questing consciousness, and all the more distinctive for that.<br /><br />There are other things in the novel I was less convinced by, such as the resolution to the mystery of what happened to Banks’ parents, which seemed uncharacteristically explicit and melodramatic. For this reason, I think, on the whole, this is the novel of Ishiguro’s I have liked least of those I have read to date. <br /><br />That is setting the bar very high, though; and <i>When We Were Orphans</i> is certainly well worth reading. Besides the memory theme, it contains interesting, intersecting reflections on national identity and colonialism and the ways in which we are formed by our childhood, all conducted in a characteristically subtle and light-handed manner, through suggestion rather than anything more direct.<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/09/24/reviews/000924.24gorra2t.html">http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/09/24...</a><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2000/mar/19/fiction.bookerprize2000">https://www.theguardian.com/books/200...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="6823449845845663963" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


