<div id="review_7714951" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/7714951" />
    <a title="Kay" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/145023-kay"><img alt="Kay" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442472119p2/145023.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/7714951?book_show_action=true">Oct 14, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kay" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kay" href="/user/show/145023-kay">Kay</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer7714951" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14503421555310670216">I&apos;ve been putting off this review for a few weeks, hoping that something inchoate in me would gell, which would make me happier than it being something incoherent in Ishiguro&apos;s writing that didn&apos;t gell. <br/><br/>Nothing gelled.<br/><br/>I&apos;ll try not to write spoilers, although as I have no idea what the denouement of this book is (let alone what it might &apos;mean&apos;) it would be hard difficult for me to know if I did - however, the strands of the story are:<br/><br/>- that the narrator is an expatriate of Shanghai, both of whose</span>
  <span id="freeText14503421555310670216" style="display:none">I've been putting off this review for a few weeks, hoping that something inchoate in me would gell, which would make me happier than it being something incoherent in Ishiguro's writing that didn't gell. <br /><br />Nothing gelled.<br /><br />I'll try not to write spoilers, although as I have no idea what the denouement of this book is (let alone what it might 'mean') it would be hard difficult for me to know if I did - however, the strands of the story are:<br /><br />- that the narrator is an expatriate of Shanghai, both of whose parents disappeared in bizarre circumstances in that city<br />- that he leaves behind his best friend who is Japanese when he is sent home to England as a little boy<br />- that he becomes England's most celebrated detective<br />- that a woman who is a form of social climber impacts on his life then marries another<br />- that he adopts a little girl<br />- that he returns to Shanghai, where he is reunited with the social climbing woman (although that is something of an injustice, she has a wider and more altruistic motive than just social bootstrapping), discovers things about his parents and his friend (or perhaps he doesn't - he may be imagining some things and forgetting others, as he has throughout the narrative) and then comes home.<br /><br />I found the novel slow and somewhat pedestrian compared to much of Ishiguro's other work, and at the end I still had no clearer picture of the narrator than I'd had from the cover blurb - nor, it seemed to me, did he have any greater insight into himself - so we went on a journey together from which neither of us seemed to gain much.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14503421555310670216" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


